[SkillPath "practice_deals/100_miscellaneous"]
[Student "S"]
{You have 23 points. You must open 2\C.

Partner responds 2\D showing 7 or fewer points.

Following partner's negative response you merely bid your suit at the cheapest level.

You bid 2\S and partner jumps to 4\S.

Now  

Partner's first response told you he has a weak hand. It didn't suddenly turn into 10 or 11 points. Partner is merely pulling a "He Who Knows, Goes" bid. He thinks you belong in 4\S.

East plays 4\S. South leads the \DQ.

<b>East plays 4\S. South leads the \DQ.</b>

Losers: \S 0 : \H 3 : \D 0 : \C 1 : Total = 4

It is possible (but not probable) that \Cs will split 3-3. 

It is possible (one chance out of two) that North holds the \HA. You could pull trumps, ending in dummy, then lead toward your \HK.

It is almost certain that you could ruff your \H loser in dummy, but only if you play a \H at trick two, leading away from your \HK. The defenders will win the \H cheaply and probably play a trump. You win dummy's \SA and play another \H which they also win. They lead a second trump which you win in your hand. You now ruff the last \H with dummy's \SJ, return to your hand, pull trumps and claim.

You cannot be defeated if you play \Hs at the second trick. 

If instead you decide to lead a \S to dummy's \SJ and lead a \H toward your \HK you might go down. South could win the \HA and play a second trump. When you played the next \H South would win again and play a third round of trumps. You would no longer be able to ruff the \H loser.}
[Play "W"]DQ

